</script></p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<p><script src="http://code.highcharts.com/highcharts.js" type="text/javascript">
</script><script src="http://code.highcharts.com/modules/exporting.js" type="text/javascript">
</script></p>","type":"text/html"},{"content":"<div id="container"></div>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>“If we were to put my mom in charge of Wal-Mart tomorrow, Wal-Mart would probably still outperform Kmart for the foreseeable future,&quot; he says. &quot;The point is: The trajectory that the company is on matters.&quot;</p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>While the impact of chief executives may be limited in the U.S., it’s even more so in much of the rest of the world. In the U.S., CEOs have more power and discretion, according to assistant professor of management at the University of Notre Dame Craig Crossland, who has studied international business culture surrounding CEOs.</p>"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>In societies where CEOs are given more discretion, &quot;we’re more likely to see big hits and big misses,” says Crossland, giving the U.S. and UK as two examples.</p>"},{"content":"<p>Western Europe and Asia differ, he says, because in those countries collectivism is more important than individualism, so CEOs are less empowered and decisions are more often made by consensus.</p>","type":"text/html"},{"type":"text/html","content":"<p>&quot;And the places we tend to see CEOs being given least discretion is in East Asia. So societies like Japan, like South Korea,” Crossland says.</p>"}]
